'''106.7 FM Rockklassiker''' is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Rock music|rock]] radio station.
Rockklassiker (formerly Classic Hits) started out as a local radio station in [[Stockholm]] in 1994,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbsradio.com/se/index.php?mod=main&top=3&parent=3&id=68 |title=SBS Radio |publisher=SBS Radio |date= |accessdate=2011-11-16}}</ref> and is today the second largest rock station in [[Sweden]] in terms of audience share.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tns-sifo.se/rapporter-undersokningar/radioresultat/tns-sifo-radioundersoekningar-rapport-i-2011 |title=TNS SIFO Radioundersökningar Rapport I 2011 - Rapporter & Undersökningar - Radioresultat &#124; TNS-SIFO |publisher=Tns-sifo.se |date=2011-04-15 |accessdate=2011-11-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125130215/http://www.tns-sifo.se/rapporter-undersokningar/radioresultat/tns-sifo-radioundersoekningar-rapport-i-2011 |archive-date=2011-01-25 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Its closest rival is [[Bandit Rock|Bandit Rock 106.3]], another radio station based in Stockholm that mainly focuses on modern and alternative rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtgradio.se/bandit-rock/ |title=Bandit Rock &#124; MTG Radio |publisher=Mtgradio.se |date= |accessdate=2011-11-16}}</ref> Rockklassiker was elected "Radio station of the year 2001" by [[The Swedish Radio Academy]].
106.7 FM Rockklassiker competes with nine other [[Commercial broadcasting|commercial]] stations in addition to six Government non-commercial stations. Its target group is 25- to 44-year-old males. Rockklassiker is today the largest [[radio station]] in this target. In Average Quarters (AQ) Rockklassiker is the 2nd largest [[Commercial broadcasting|commercial]] radio station in the market. Rockklassiker has been a consistent high performer in the ratings over the last couple of years.
