The '''Asia-Pacific Space Cooperation Organization''' ('''APSCO''') is an inter-governmental organization operated as a non-profit independent body with full international legal status. It is headquartered in [[Beijing]], [[People's Republic of China]].

Members include agencies from:<ref>[http://www.apsco.int/member.aspx Member states] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622062836/http://www.apsco.int/member.aspx |date=June 22, 2010 }} list on APSCO website</ref> [[Space Research and Remote Sensing Organization|Bangladesh]], [[China National Space Administration|China]], [[Iranian Space Agency|Iran]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20100210223300/http://ictpa.gov.mn/ Mongolia], [[Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission|Pakistan]], [http://www.conida.gob.pe/ Peru], and [https://web.archive.org/web/20100123055752/http://www.mict.go.th/main.php?filename=index Thailand].

[[Indonesia]] and [[Turkey]] also signed the APSCO convention.<ref name="new members 2006">[http://www.pakistantimes.net/2006/06/22/top3.htm Turkey joins Pakistan, China in joint efforts for Space Technology] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616055744/http://www.pakistantimes.net/2006/06/22/top3.htm |date=June 16, 2008 }}</ref>

In 2005, the APSCO convention was signed in Beijing.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

Representatives from [[Argentina]], [[Malaysia]], the [[Philippines]], [[Russia]] and [[Sri Lanka]] also attended the founding ceremony.<ref>http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-12/16/content_10514901.htm</ref>

Its stated objectives are:<ref name="convention">[http://www.apsco.int/UploadFile/2009924/F1TKF8A2009924.pdf Convention of the Asia-Pacific Space Cooperation Organization (APSCO)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708164434/http://www.apsco.int/UploadFile/2009924/F1TKF8A2009924.pdf |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref>
# To promote and strengthen the development of collaborative space programs among its Member States by establishing the basis for cooperation in  peaceful applications of space science and technology;
# To take effective actions to assist the Member States in such areas as space technological research and development, applications and training by elaborating and implementing space development policies;
# To promote cooperation, joint development, and to share achievements among the Member States in space technology and its applications as well as in space science research by tapping the cooperative potential of the region.
# To enhance cooperation among relevant enterprises and institutions of the Member States and to promote the industrialization of space technology and its applications.
# To contribute to the peaceful uses of outer space in the international cooperative activities in space technology and its applications.

As of 2010, the organization has defined 10 projects on designing, building and launching light satellites, middle class satellites weighing 500–600&nbsp;kg, research satellites, remote-sensing and telecommunications satellites.<ref>http://www.payvand.com/news/10/oct/1160.html</ref>

