{{Infobox rockunit | name = Gibraltar Limestone | image = File:North face of Rock of Gibraltar.jpg | caption = North face of the Rock of Gibraltar | type = [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]] | age = [[Early Jurassic]] | period = Early Jurassic | prilithology = | otherlithology = | namedfor = | namedby = | region = | country = [[Gibraltar]] | coordinates = | unitof = | subunits = | underlies = | overlies = | thickness = | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }}
'''Gibraltar Limestone''' consists of greyish-white or pale-gray compact, and sometime finely crystalline, medium to thick bedded limestones and [[dolomite]]s that locally contain chert seams. This [[Formation (stratigraphy)|formation]] comprises about three quarters of the [[Rock of Gibraltar]] near the southernmost tip of the [[Iberian peninsula]]. Geologists have found various poorly preserved and badly eroded and rolled [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[fossil]]s within it. The fossils found in the Gibraltar Limestone include various [[brachiopod]]s, [[coral]]s, echinoid fragments, [[gastropod]]s, [[pelecypod]]s, and [[stromatolite]]s. These fossils indicate an Early Jurassic age (Lower Lias) for the deposition of the Gibraltar Limestone.<ref>Rose, E. P. F., and M. S. Rosenbaum (1991). ''A Field Guide to the Geology of Gibraltar''. Gibraltar: The Gibraltar Museum. p. 192.</ref>
