{{Politics of Swaziland}}

A '''parliamentary election''' was held in [[Swaziland]] for the [[House of Assembly of Swaziland|House of Assembly]] on 19 September 2008.<ref>[http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90855/6463488.html Swaziland sets parliamentary poll for Sept. 19], Xinhua (''People's Daily Online''), 31 July 2008</ref> It was the first election under the new constitution introduced in 2006, and the first time that foreign observers were allowed to monitor an election in the country.<ref name=BBC>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7624634.stm Swazis vote in controversial poll], BBC News, 19 September 2008</ref>  It was observed by an Expert Team established by the Commonwealth Secretary-General at the request of the Elections and Boundaries Commission of Swaziland.<ref name="SNE2008">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecommonwealth.org/files/184644/FileName/SwazilandNationalElections2008-CETReportFinalPrint.pdf|title=Swaziland National Elections, 19 September 2008|publisher=Commonwealth Secretariat|accessdate=2009-10-14|location=London}}</ref>  

On the day before the election, several union officials were arrested for attempting to block the border with [[South Africa]] at [[Oshoek]] for a pro-democracy protest.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7622667.stm Police hold Swazi poll protesters] BBC News, 18 September 2008</ref>

Political parties remained banned in Swaziland, so all candidates for the 55 seats were [[Independent (politician)|independents]].<ref name=BBC/> Following the election, [[List of kings of Swaziland|King]] [[Mswati III of Swaziland|Mswati III]] was to appoint 10 more MPs. The National Assembly would then elect 10 members for the [[Senate of Swaziland|Senate]], with the King appointing 20 more.<ref name=BBC/>

